description:
TRIGGER WARNING for some pretty heavy and frank discussions about mental illness and all the dark serious stuff that comes with it.

Here's a playlist of songs inspired by this video: https://open.spotify.com/playlist/15HV2QOQoiVDkLCjjAppjt?si=f1d11d73ddde46bc

The song featured at the end of the video is TEETH by St. Terrible, which you can find in the playlist above. Thanks to the band for supplying me with an instrumental mix to use. St. Terrible is one of my favorite bands ever and you should listen to them.

This topic has always been something that really bothered me and I'm finally getting around to why I think this gesture is not healthy, a bit toxic, and kinda needs to be addressed seriously.

I'm a huge fan of bands like Twenty One Pilots, My Chemical Romance, the Used, Motion City Soundtrack, and tons of other artists who explore heavier topics in their lyrics and messaging. However, with them comes a type of fan that tends to go overboard with their adoration of the project. While there's a humanity in the claim that a band "saved someone's life," I think it's misguided. What makes me worried is that it's mostly teenagers with this mentality.

At the end of the day, you are your own hero and the fact that you're here watching this video and reading these words are proof enough. You owe it to yourself to give credit where it's due, and that's not to anyone but yourself. You're awesome.

I'll make less existentially terrifying videos soon I promise, I just needed to talk about this. It's been bugging me for months.

I hope you're doing well. You know what phone numbers to call and what people to talk to if things are in crisis mode right now.

Come to the album release party on December 10th at the Shredder in Boise Idaho to see us perform ALL of these songs! Doors at 6, music at 7. All ages. $10 will get you admission and a free copy of the album.

After 7 years of writing, recording, re-recording, mixing, and mastering, it's finally here: The Dentonweaver. Raccoon Tour's debut album that was first announced in 2018.

Here it is: The album I've spent most of my life working on in one form or another.

This dumb album followed me through most of my high school years and is deeply inspired by the melodramatic antisocial adventures I went on with friends. They're personified here, all taking place in a fictionalized version of Converse County.

Dentonweaver is a huge anthemic crash course through the different sounds and vibes in the album. Mt. Hekla is a synthy pop song about being in love during the end of the world. Converse County is a monstrous and sad behemoth. Trophy Street is a cold and melancholy ditty. Nightmare Eyes gets spooky and dreamy. Mischief Night is a tight-knit pipe bomb. Horrorshow is a collaboration with underground legend Heccra. F#%$ is a petty and self deprecating breakup jam. Sofarinrunning is a nostalgic ballad. Funeral Song is a slow-build catharsis with an explosive ending. I find that when I have an idea of what to look for, consuming full albums becomes easier. I dunno. I worked hard on this. Let me be excited right here.

All artwork done by the amazing Sarah Reiners.

Thank you to the folks who made the hundreds of memes on Instagram about how this would never come out. The ball is now in your court.

title: Horror Movie Survival Guide
description:
Happy spooky season y'all.

Visit https://linktr.ee/RaccoonTour to pick up some fun limited edition merch before our big release on October 29!

Here we have a few tips on how to make the horror movie viewing experience enjoyable as well as a boat load of recommendations.

I mean this video is pretty much a ton of recommendations essentially. Some of them get pretty serious towards the end of the video. I had a rough time editing this and revisiting some of them, too. Hot dang.

I have this theory that horror movies can be described with any combo of 2 of these 4 descriptors: Spooky, gory, goofy, and Ruin Your Day. That pretty much introduces 6 microgenres:

Spooky/Goofy is fun silly Halloween stuff that's lighthearted.

Spooky/Gory is a bit more violent and vicious with strong supernatural elements.

Spooky/Ruin Your Day is pure misery where the ghosts are out to kick your dog, burn your house down, ruin your credit score, and THEN dispatch you and your family.

Goofy/Gory is where all the gleeful and sometimes satirical body horror lies.

Goofy/Ruin Your Day is... weird. You'll see.

Finally, there's Gory/Ruin Your Day which is unadulterated vicious stimuli to make you feel bad for 2 hours. This is intense stuff.

Proceed with caution. This video is a bit more intense than my others.

Also did I mention my band is releasing our debut single on October 29? You should definitely check it out and see us live in Boise, Idaho on the same day if you're in the neighborhood.

description:

You can also support my fun little music project by visiting raccoontour.net. You'll be hearing about an album from us very shortly. We're just a few baby steps away from being done and ready to announce.

Also visit my friend Ezra on Instagram @FearOfSubsisting. They're pretty cool.

Sometimes I have kids tell me that their teachers play my videos in their classrooms and stuff. It's my job to make sure that never happens again.

Scaled and Icy was a super divisive and controversial album. I weigh in with my own thoughts with my best friend Ezra. Together we make fools of ourselves and ramble about nothing or like 25 minutes.

The original footage was 90 minutes. Trust me, you're not missing much.

Also just a lil PSA, if ur gonna be dumb like us and get intoxicated and stuff, always make sure you're in a safe and secured place with people you trust. Never ever get into a vehicle under the influence. No exceptions. While getting inebriated like this certainly isn't the most responsible thing to do, I'll always make sure to set an example by doing so safely.

By the way, that TOP burrito was super good. Ate the whole thing, which I'm never able to do with Chipotle burritos. Those things are thicc.

I'm just now realizing that this is my first video in like... 5? 6 months? Yeah what a grand comeback video huh. I'd love to make more fun videos like this, just gotta beat out those sweet sweet depression vibes.

Fun fact: YouTube tends to like it when you litter your description with tags and relevant terms. For example, for this video, I could write Twenty One Pilots, Trench, Blurryface, Stressed Out, Tyler Joseph, Josh Dunn, Ukulele, Clique, Fueled By Ramen, Shy Away, Choker, Saturday, DEMA, Lyrics, Review, Music, Quarantine, Review, and so on and so forth.

Also, man, it has been a while. I hope you're doing okay. Family doing alright? Friends and health and stuff going fine? I hope so. You're a good noodle, you deserve nice things like that. I've been doing meh-so-so. Got a full time job that sucked my energy and motivation to do anything except work and sleep. Cut down my hours so I can work on YouTube videos and music more often.

Oh yeah, Sophomore Year video will be coming out this summer hopefully. It's turning into a monster of a video.

In this special lil meditation on existential nihilism and Terror Management Theory, I try my darned hardest to answer a really easy question: Why do anything?

I know this is some pretty intense and heavy subject matter, but I really hope you watching this will come away from this feeling energized and motivated rather than bummed and stuff. Everything kinda does suck for everyone, especially right now. But that's kinda more the reason to continue tricking yourself that it doesn't.

All we have is our perception of the world and our day to day experiences. Why throw that away, ya know?

The brilliant song at the end is "Nothingness Vs. The Optimistic Spirit" by St. Terrible, my favorite artist in the northwest United States. Check it out on Spotify and stuff if you can.

By the way! I kinda tasked myself with a challenge for this video: I wanted movement in EVERY SINGLE SECOND of this project. No still stick dudes running through lines like a Powerpoint. I'm kinda experimenting to make my videos a lil more visually interesting. If you thought this was a neat lil thingiemabobber, please let me know. I'm very self conscious and nervous about trying new things.

BY THE WAY SOME DISCLAIMERS!

This video is kinda approaching this topic from a secular perspective. If you're like "but the Bible says sdfjkahfkjdhaskfdh" we're not gonna get anywhere. We're on two very different planes of information to compare and contrast. I talk about religion stuff more in-depth in my other video, "My Thoughts on Religion."

"But Nate, we don't completely know if-" Listen dude, you're free to think whatever you'd like. That's cool. I'm not here to change minds or anything, I'm just here to think out loud and draw silly stick people and whatever. But when you assert some level of uncertainty on the very fabrics of reality, our understanding of the laws of nature, and so on so forth... You're kinda going toe-to-toe with brilliant scientists who have dedicated their lives to understanding, testing, and experimenting with this stuff. The scientific method is never 100% certain on anything, but it's often 99.9% sure about most of the stuff it asserts. Just because you don't completely understand how something works doesn't mean it's untrue. It's your responsibility to educate yourself.

"But Nate, the meaning of life is a test! We're put here to make our own decisions, to be good people! Choosing between good and evil, free will, so on so forth!" This is not a very well thought-out assertion like... at all dawg. It basically comes down to this: If God is omnipotent, he's in control of whether or not injustice is a necessary foil to extract obligatory meaning out of anything. He also knows the outcome of all moral situations he throws his creations into. Either god is bound to pre-existing ideals or he's evil. title: Reviewing Trench by Twenty One Pilots dRUNK
description:
COME SAY HI ON PATREON! Patreon.com/NateIsLame

Oh boy this is a very serious and legitimate review of the new Twenty One Pilots album "Trench." I pirated it a few days early and have been bopping it ever since.

I think it's the best thing since Betty White. I say "Betty White" because she's literally older than sliced bread. You can Google that. So instead of saying "Best thing since sliced bread," we should say "Best thing since Betty White."

All of these songs are so good holy cow. I mean I know I rip into a few of them but, let's be honest here, I wasn't in the best headspace reviewing this album.

On Twitter, I did a song by song reaction for this album. I'm going to post it in its entirety so this description will be long and the SEO score will be better.

Jumpsuit- We already know this song is radical. It hits HARD and is a lot more intense than any of their other music. I want a punk band to cover this.

Levitate- Sick flow. Clever lyrics. But not single quality and it's certainly not a stand-out. Almost feels like an overstuffed skit.

Morph- WOW. Old timey Twenty One Pilots sound with new and improved lyrics. The callbacks to Nicholas Bourbaki were SUPER clever and almost fourth wall breaking. The ties to the DEMA website were subtle and rewarding for fans and not annoying for casuals. EXCELLENT JAM.

My Blood- Feels like a darker MGMT in the chorus. This track has grown on me since I first heard it. A fun arena banger and sick dichotomy of dark and grimy and the clean, polished, and spacey chorus. I'm digging it.

Chlorine- Intro bit gave me chills. Chill urban vibe almost. Lyrics are dark as FRICK and the gleeful delivery is genuinely spooky. This is boundary-pushing for them. This would be fantastic on ukulele. This would benefit from piano tho. THE BRIDGE AND OUTRO WOW!! Favorite so far.

Smithereens- CUTE. Very cute. The spacey vibe is starting to become defined and distinct. But... the first song on the record that doesn't really super immediately stick out? I didn't like it as much as Tear in my Heart, the other song for Jenna. The DEMA theme is fading.

Neon Gravestones- H O L Y F R I C K . This hit hard. My god. I feel like I'm 14 again. This is a powerful message, an important deviation from the common message spread throughout society. The sound, the atmosphere, and the powerful verses at the end. This is important and truly masterful musical craftsmanship. It's self-reflective and it feels real. This no longer feels like Twenty One Pilots the band, but rather Tyler Joseph feeling tinges of guilt for the culture he's created for mental illness. It's sad, inspiring, and remarkable. 10/10.

The Hype- A great breather from the last track. UNEXPECTED UKULELE! Fantastic bridge. EXCELLENT LAST CHORUS! Piano, synth, layered vocals, excellent lyrics. Feels like a natural progression, taking the best elements of Blurryface and Vessel. Awesome outro. God I love this album.

Nico and the Niners- Probably my least favorite thus far, and that's pretty remarkable since this song is still pretty fun. The DEMA thematic material feels out of place now though, since the album has barely discussed it up until now. The lyrics are bizarre in context of Trench.

Cut My Lip- I'm waiting for this song to take off. It's not really going anywhere. It feels like a long intro that keeps evolving and not changing. Poor dynamics. Waiting for the bridge to save things. It didn't. Neat interlude though. The song kinda went nowhere. Least fave.

Bandito- NOT how I imagined it'd sound. Vibey. Atmospheric. Builds nice and evenly. It feels as if something is festering under the song waiting to be released. In the true spirit of Self Titled but much more restrained. Gorgeous bridge and haunting vox. Beautiful last 2 minutes.

Pet Cheetah- What are these lyrics? The Trench formula and sound is starting to show its strings with this song. I'm sure there's some deeper message here, but there should definitely be a more serious way to express it. Horror dubstep? What??? Not fantastic but not awful.

Legend- Already kinda heard this through a Twitter leak. Fun, has Vessel vibes. Ukulele! Heartbreaking lyrics. Wow. Serious bummer material. Sounds happy but is really sad. What a novel concept. Jon Bellion vibes toward the end with the synthy horn. The outro is CRUSHING.

Leave The City- Heartfelt, written to be played live. This song is a grower. A dark and unexpected ending for the DEMA concept. I just wish the theme surrounding the album was explored and concluded a bit more tactfully. It's pretty and nice, but doesn't really do much.
